<refentry xmlns="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink"
        xmlns:svg="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"
        xmlns:db="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook" xmlns:scilab="http://www.scilab.org"
        xml:lang="en" xml:id="operator_expand">
    <refnamediv>
        <refname>operator_expand</refname>
        <refpurpose>Automatic expansion of singleton dimensions in binary operators</refpurpose>
    </refnamediv>
    <refsynopsisdiv>
        <title>Syntax</title>
        <synopsis>
            X op Y
        </synopsis>
    </refsynopsisdiv>
    <refsection>
        <title>Arguments</title>
        <variablelist>
            <varlistentry>
                <term>X, Y</term>
                <listitem>
                    <para>
                        Scalars, vectors, matrices or hypermatrices of numbers (real or complex),
                        encoded integers, polynomials or texts, according to the operator being
                        applied.
                    </para>
                </listitem>
            </varlistentry>
        </variablelist>
    </refsection>
    <refsection>
        <title>Description</title>
        <para>
            Expanding automatically replicates any dimension equal to <literal>1</literal>
            so that both operands get identical shapes before applying an element-wise binary
            operator. Missing trailing dimensions are considered to be <literal>1</literal>.
            The resulting size is the per-dimension maximum of both shapes.
        </para>
        <para>
            A scalar is just a special case where all dimensions are singletons, so scalar
            expansion is naturally covered by expanding.
        </para>
        <para>
            Expanding is currently implemented for the following operators:
            <literal>+</literal> (addition), <literal>-</literal> (subtraction),
            <literal>.*</literal> (element-wise multiplication),
            <literal>./</literal> (element-wise right division),
            and <literal>.^</literal> (element-wise power).
        </para>
    </refsection>
    <refsection>
        <title>Examples</title>
    <programlisting role="example"><![CDATA[
// Addition with expand
a = [1; 2];
b = [10 20 30];
a + b
 ]]></programlisting>
    <screen><![CDATA[
--> a = [1; 2];
--> b = [10 20 30];
--> a + b
 ans  =
   11.   21.   31.
   12.   22.   32.
]]></screen>
    <programlisting role="example"><![CDATA[
// Subtraction with expand
a = [1; 2];
b = [10 20 30];
b - a
 ]]></programlisting>
    <screen><![CDATA[
--> b - a
 ans  =
   9.    19.   29.
   8.    18.   28.
]]></screen>
    <programlisting role="example"><![CDATA[
// Element-wise multiplication with expand
a = [1; 2; 3];
b = [10 20];
a .* b
 ]]></programlisting>
    <screen><![CDATA[
--> a = [1; 2; 3];
--> b = [10 20];
--> a .* b
 ans  =
   10.   20.
   20.   40.
   30.   60.
]]></screen>
    <programlisting role="example"><![CDATA[
// Element-wise division with expand
a = [100; 200];
b = [1 2 4];
a ./ b
 ]]></programlisting>
    <screen><![CDATA[
--> a = [100; 200];
--> b = [1 2 4];
--> a ./ b
 ans  =
   100.   50.   25.
   200.   100.  50.
]]></screen>
    <programlisting role="example"><![CDATA[
// Element-wise power with expand
a = [2; 3];
b = [1 2 3];
a .^ b
 ]]></programlisting>
    <screen><![CDATA[
--> a = [2; 3];
--> b = [1 2 3];
--> a .^ b
 ans  =
   2.   4.   8.
   3.   9.   27.
]]></screen>
    <programlisting role="example"><![CDATA[
// Complex doubles
ca = [1+%i; -2+2*%i];
cb = [%i, 2-%i, -1+3*%i];
ca + cb
 ]]></programlisting>
    <screen><![CDATA[
--> ca = [1+%i; -2+2*%i];
--> cb = [%i, 2-%i, -1+3*%i];
--> ca + cb
 ans  =
   1. + 2.i   3. + 0.i  0. + 4.i
  -2. + 3.i   0. + i   -3. + 5.i
]]></screen>
    <programlisting role="example"><![CDATA[
// Polynomials
pcol = [%s; 1 + %s];
prow = [%s^2, 2 - %s];
pcol + prow
 ]]></programlisting>
    <screen><![CDATA[
--> pcol = [%s; 1 + %s];
--> prow = [%s^2, 2 - %s];
--> pcol + prow
 ans  =
   s +s^2       2
   1. +s +s^2   3
]]></screen>
    <programlisting role="example"><![CDATA[
// Incompatible shapes still fail
[1 2; 3 4] + ones(3, 2)
 ]]></programlisting>
    <screen><![CDATA[
--> [1 2; 3 4] + ones(3, 2)

Operator +: Wrong dimensions for operation [2x2] + [3x2], same dimensions expected.
]]></screen>
